The game will transform the endless runner into a 
\f1\b dungeon progression
\f0\b0  with segmented levels or waves. Each \'93dungeon run\'94 is infinite but divided into 
\f1\b stages
\f0\b0  (floors or zones), where the player clears waves of enemies and obstacles before reaching a boss. After defeating a boss, the player descends to the next dungeon stage, which is more difficult and introduces new surprises. This structure provides short-term goals (reach the next boss) and long-term progression (survive as many stages as possible){\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ejaw.net/what-is-an-endless-runner-game/#:~:text=Well,or%20big%20purchases%20provide%20longevity"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 ejaw.net}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Waves & Levels:
\f0\b0  During a stage, enemies spawn in waves as the player runs. Early waves are small and simple, giving the player time to react and learn patterns. As the player advances, waves grow larger and more complex, with mixed enemy types and occasional mini-bosses. To keep the endless run interesting, 
\f1\b each stage has a distinct theme or environment with unique enemies
\f0\b0  (e.g. a crypt with undead, a lava cave with fire monsters). This approach is similar to how Pixel Dungeon\'92s endless mode assigns random themes per depth to vary monster \
\

\f1\b Difficulty Scaling:
\f0\b0  The game should 
\f1\b ramp up difficulty gradually and fairly
\f0\b0 . Enemies gain increased health, damage, and speed with each new stage, and new enemy abilities appear over time. However, avoid making it too hard too quickly \'96 endless runners that spike in difficulty too fast will frustrate new players{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ejaw.net/what-is-an-endless-runner-game/#:~:text=Endless%20runner%20games%20always%20get,improve%20their%20skills%20that%20quickly"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 ejaw.net}}. Instead, follow a gentle difficulty curve early on and accelerate later. For instance, Stage 1 is forgiving (slower enemies, simple attack patterns), but by Stage 5+ the enemies are faster and more numerous. Ensure the spawn rate of obstacles and enemies increases at a 
\f1\b \'93good pace\'94
\f0\b0  so that skilled players feel challenged while beginners can still improve{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ejaw.net/what-is-an-endless-runner-game/#:~:text=Developers%20must%20carefully%20plan%20how,bore%20better%20players%20to%20quit"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 ejaw.net}}. You can implement a scaling factor that increases every stage or every few waves, affecting enemy spawn counts and stats.\

\f1\b Pacing and Balance:
\f0\b0  Introduce natural 
\f1\b peaks and valleys
\f0\b0  in the action. After a tough wave, consider a brief respite (a few seconds of lighter obstacle running or a fountain that heals the player) to let the player catch their breath. Each boss fight serves as a climax, followed by a rewarding loot phase (detailed below) that acts as a tension release before the next stage\'92s buildup. This 
\f1\b rhythm of challenge and reward
\f0\b0  keeps players engaged without feeling overwhelmed. Also, periodically introduce 
\f1\b new mechanics or enemies
\f0\b0  as progression rewards \'96 for example, a new trap type appears in later stages, or an elite enemy with special behavior shows up occasionally. These surprises serve as fresh content to maintain player engagement{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ejaw.net/what-is-an-endless-runner-game/#:~:text=Even%20perfect%20levels%20can%E2%80%99t%20sustain,same%20experience%20without%20new%20updates"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 ejaw.net}} beyond the basic running loop.\
To keep the structure modular, use a 
\f1\b Level Manager
\f0\b0  module that controls stage transitions, enemy wave configuration, and difficulty parameters. For example, define a list of stages with associated enemy types, environmental art, and scaling values. This way, adding a new stage or tweaking difficulty is as simple as editing data (no deep code changes). The Level Manager can trigger events like \'93boss incoming\'94 or \'93stage complete\'94 which other systems (UI, audio) listen to, making the architecture scalable and easy to extend.\
